#Frida, 18x24 inches, acrylic gouache and mixed media collage. 

“I am not sick. I am broken. But I am happy as long as I can paint.” 

I’ll always be drawn to Frida. Her story is so much like mine. Like me, Frida was disabled by an infectious disease as a child. She contracted polio, I contracted bacterial meningitis. The virus did damage to her right leg and foot, like mine. She also limped like me. Although she didn’t have amputations, she certainly dealt with a lifetime of pain— Turning to her art as a way to heal, cope and create beauty through disability.

Sometimes I find myself stuck, how unfair pain and trauma can make a person feel. And then there’s art. And music. And writing. And inspiring women like Frida Kayla. Frida’s many self portraits are a reminder to never stop. Make your differences your blessings. And most importantly to me— always believe in your ability to overcome everything life throws your way. 

P.S. Polio and meningitis are vaccine preventable today. ❤️🙌

#disabledandproud

Samantha’s Butterflies, 18x24, acrylic gauche, mixed media. 

This art was inspired by my old art history book from college. The book stared at me everyday in my art studio, reminding me of the lack of women artists in history. So almost 30 years having being assigned that book, I finally grabbed it and cut it to pieces. 

I will never forget being a young art student and our female instructor telling the girls in class to look around. First, she wanted us to notice there weren’t very many females in the class. Secondly, she said to check our art history books. We were missing from them. Lastly, she told us not to give up our creative passions once we had families. That too often art is looked at as a hobby for women and we are expected to toss it aside when we have families. 

And sure, times have changed since the 90’s, but that advice stuck with me for years. Even today, as I struggle with the energy to balance family life and creative workflow, I remind myself of those history books… Where women were subjects, but often not the creators. 🦋🎨 It is not easy. Change begins with a positive role model. Be the voice that lifts women artists and be the support that helps women not only succeed, but thrive in their creative fields. Thank you all for your support and for giving me this amazing platform to share my journey. 🦋🎨🦋🎨🦋
#womeninart 

@femalequotient @the_female_lead @femalecollective

Thank you so much to the @columbusdispatch for sharing my voice and my story. This first clip in the article hit my heart— That is an old photo and my cousin Lilly in this clip with me. Although meningitis did not take her, she left us suddenly at 20 years old. Her loss has stuck with our family forever— when I first began to advocate for meningitis, I met parents grieving the loss of their teens and young college aged children and my family knew their pain on too many levels. Please learn about the dangers of meningitis and how you can protect your family. I’ll link the article on my page. Thanks again for the community support from my community. And Columbus Dispatch. ❤️

To 2023 and so many awesome books and book covers! Not that I judge a book by its cover! 😂 Right… I LOVE a good cover and love it more when the book and the cover are amazing. 

Here’s some of my favorite books of 2023:

Tomorrow, and Tomorrow, and Tomorrow by Gabrielle Zevin @gabriellezevin 
🎮❤️My book cover glows. For real. This story was nothing what I expected. It’s about video games and not about video games at all. It deserves every second of praise it received and more. 

No Two Persons by Erica Bauermeister @ericabauermeisterauthor 
💙 It’s the book for story lovers and the story lover’s book. I will never stop telling people how much I loved this! “No two people ever read the same book twice.” 

Hello Beautiful  by Ann Napolitano @annnapolitano 
💚 The family drama. The heartache. It’s beautiful. And that cover! No, I didn’t paint that, but my soul speaks those brushstrokes.

The Collected Regrets of Clover by Mikki Brammer  @mikkibrammer ✨🖤 Sigh! NYC, a death doula and a story about humanity at its core. Bonus: UK cover! Love it so much. 

The Unmaking of June Farrow by Adrienne Young @adrienneyoungbooks ✨🖤✨ It’s a little creepy, a little mysterious, deeply romantic and magical. Twists and turns and fun. 

Weyward by Emilia Hart @emiliahartbooks ✨🖤 Goodbye Earls everywhere. Bye a-holes, bye! So very good. Haunting. Amazing. 

Amazing Grace Adams by Fran Littlewood @_franlittlewood ❤️ It’s a quick, not so lighthearted read, that gives you a little dark humor and lots feels. Moms in their 40’s with hormones rejoice. Bonus: That cover! I love me brave woman and a middle finger. 

Fourth Wing (The Empyrean #1) by Rebecca Yarros @rebeccayarros 💛🐉 Made me love dragons and I didn’t think anyone after Jon Snow was going to accomplish that one! Read it and listened— 600 freakin pages! 

Tom Lake by Ann Patchett @annpatchettgough_writer 💙💚 There’s no passing up an Ann Patchett book with daisies on the cover and Meryl Streep reading it! 

Last but not least: Sinead! @oconnor.sinead My heart is still trying to recover. I’ll love her forever. 

📚🙌 Thanks to @NetGalley for giving me more than half of this list as an early review copy.
